						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">In <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?p=63436#63436" class="postlink">this post</a>, blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Oh yeah, always be sure to check the return value from fclose() when you've written to a file.</div>
<br />What should a program do if fclose() returns EOF with one of the errno values listed on <a href="http://www.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/000095399/functions/fclose.html" class="postlink">this page</a>? The underlying stream is still open because fclose() failed, but the FILE * is destroyed. Can I expect fclose() to fail even if the fflush() right before it succeeded? And on that note, what should a program do if fflush() fails with an errno value listed listed <a href="http://www.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/000095399/functions/fflush.html" class="postlink">here</a>?</div>

