						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">An fclose() failing isn't a program bug; it's a normal occurrence in some run-time cases. Using assert() to catch this is itself a bug, since assert is for finding bugs in the program, not validating external conditions. So maybe in this case assert is finding a bug, that being the assert itself. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /></div>
<br />
<br />well, that depends on which platform you are using... perhaps it's just me, but i rather have a false positive indication of that there might be a problem than no a indication at all. and assert() will only be pressent in a debug environment anyway so i don't really see the problem <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" />
<br />
<br />@tepples: i don't think it's necessary to check if the logfile couldn't close, especially if the last thing you did to the file was a flush.
<br />
<br />if you really want to make sure you don't destroy a document, don't open it for anything other than reading (then it doesn't matter if fclose fails) or just create a copy of the original before you write anything and then if it fails, you atleast have a backup file you can recover <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /></div>

